<DOC><DOCNO> AP880729-0316 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 0602EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   07-29 0521</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0544</SECOND><DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The $660 million leveraged buyout of KoppersCo.'s chemicals business has apparently hit a snag, putting a hitchin Brian Beazer's plan to use the proceeds to help finance his $1.8billion takeover of Koppers.   The British industrialist, who prevailed June 1 in a bittertakeover battle against Koppers' former management, did not denythe rumors, which surfaced Thursday, nor would he reaffirm aprediction he made Monday that the chemicals buyout would closeAug. 8.</TEXT><DATELINE>TWINSBURG, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Revco D.S. Inc., a giant drugstore chain,has filed for bankruptcy protection, a month after missing a $46million interest payment to bondholders, officials disclosed.   Revco Chairman Boake A. Sells said Thursday the stage was setfor the reorganization filing when Revco failed to pay the intereston $400 million in junk bonds June 15. Bondholders were demandingpayment of the principal as well as the interest.   Revco issued the bonds to finance its $1.5 billion leveragedbuyout in late 1986. When it missed the interest payment, the Revcobuyout became the largest leveraged buyout to fail.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Merrill Lynch andamp; Co. stockbroker has been firedfollowing an internal investigation into whether he traded stockswith advance knowledge of Business Week magazine articles, thesecurities firm said.   The giant brokerage house said Thursday that William Dillon, 33,a financial consultant in its New London, Conn., office, wasterminated after company lawyers uncovered records suggestingstocks might have been bought and sold on tips from articles due tobe published in the mass-circulation magazine.   The dismissal came a week after Business Week said it wasprobing pre-publication trading linked to its ``Inside WallStreet'' column.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Two major U.S. airlines said their after-tax profit rosestrongly in the latest quarter from a year earlier, boosted byrevenue gains generated by growth in passenger traffic.   UAL Corp., the parent of United, the nation's largest airline,on Thursday reported a 134 percent jump in second-quarter profit to$124.2 million, or $5.77 a share.   Delta, the third-largest U.S. carrier, posted a 76 percent boostin profit in the fourth quarter of its fiscal year, to $103.28million, or $2.11 a share.</TEXT><DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The U.S. Postal Service began a 16-month,$700,000 quest to lick the problem of stamps that don't stay stuck,urging industry to produce an adhesive to serve as a ``seat beltfor a stamp.''   Gordon C. Morison, a senior assistant postmaster general, madeit clear Thursday that the post office was serious aboutdevelopment of a superior, water-activated adhesive.   He said the Postal Service would spend nearly $90 million thisyear for stamps, sales of which would generate about $8 billion.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market advanced Thursday as the Dow Jones average of30 industrials rose 28.63 points to 2,082.33.   The dollar rose against major currencies. Gold prices were mixed.   Bond prices finished unchanged to slightly lower.   Corn and sugar futures fell sharply while most wheat and soybeanfutures slipped. Crude oil futures were little changed.</TEXT></DOC>